'''David Steven "Dave" Brown''' (January 16, 1953 <U+2013> January 10, 2006) was an [[American football]] player and coach.  

Brown played 15 seasons in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) at the [[cornerback]] position for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] from 1976 to 1986, the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in 1975 and the [[Green Bay Packers]] from 1987 to 1989. He was selected as a second-team All-NFL player in 1984 and a second-team All-AFC player in 1985. His 62 career interceptions ranks ninth in NFL history, and his 50 interceptions with the Seahawks remains a club record.  

Brown also played [[college football]] as a [[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|safety]] and [[punt returner]] for the [[University of Michigan]] from 1972 to 1974. While playing for Michigan, compiled 526 punt return yards (11.7 yards per return), three punt returns for touchdowns, 174 tackles, nine interceptions, 202 interception return yards, and 15 pass breakups. He was selected as a consensus first-team [[defensive back]] on the [[1973 College Football All-America Team]] and a unanimous first-team pick on the [[1974 College Football All-America Team]].  He was posthumously inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 2007.

In his later years, Brown pursued a career in coaching.  He was the defensive backs coach for the Seattle Seahawks from 1992 to 1998 and for the [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football]] team from 2001 until his death in January 2006.

==Early years==
Brown was born in [[Akron, Ohio]], in 1953.<ref name=PFR>{{cite web|title=Dave Brown|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrowDa01.htm}}</ref>  His father, Asa Brown, was a skilled rubber worker at a Goodyear tire plant in Akron.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dave Brown's Dad: The Proudest Man|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press|date=May 14, 1975|author=Pat Livingston|page=61|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19750514&id=QOwjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=C1YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2176,5425115&hl=en}}</ref>  Brown played high school football at [[Garfield High School (Akron, Ohio)|Garfield High School]] in Akron.  He began as a [[quarterback]] before being converted into a [[wide receiver]] and [[defensive back]].<ref name=MD/>

==University of Michigan==
Brown enrolled at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1971 and played [[college football]] as a [[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|safety]] and [[punt returner]] for head coach [[Bo Schembechler]]'s [[Michigan Wolverines football]] teams from 1972 to 1974.<ref name=Roster>{{cite web|title=All-Time Football Roster Database|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|accessdate=March 26, 2015|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/rosters/football.php}}</ref>  Recruited to Michigan as a [[wide receiver]],<ref name=MD>{{cite news|title=Brown shines at bringing 'em down|newspaper=The Michigan Daily|date=October 3, 1973|page=6|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2706&dat=19731004&id=QBZKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tx4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1481,1702600&hl=en}}</ref> Brown played on both offense and defense for Michigan's all-freshman football team in 1971.<ref name=HOF/>

As a sophomore, Brown started all 11 games at the safety position for the [[1972 Michigan Wolverines football team]] that compiled a 10-1 record and allowed opponents to score only 57 points (5.2 points per game).<ref>{{cite web|title=1972 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1972fbt.htm}}</ref> Brown had three interceptions in 1972, including two interceptions in one game against Minnesota for 82 return yards.<ref name=SY/>  He also contributed 11 punt returns for 189 yards (including an 83-yard return for touchdown against Navy), 73 tackles, eight pass breakups and two fumble recoveries to the 1972 Wolverines.<ref name=SY>{{cite web|title=Michigan Football Statistic Archive Query Page|publisher=University of Michigan|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://stats.ath.umich.edu/football/footstart.php}}(to retrieve information for a particular season, go to "Games & Totals by Season" and select the year for which statistics are to be retrieved)</ref> At the end of his sophomore season, Brown was selected as a first-team defensive back on the [[1972 All-Big Ten Conference football team]].<ref>{{cite news|title=UM, State, Buckeyes Dominate UPI's All Big Ten Team |newspaper=Ludington Daily News (UPI story)|date=November 28, 1972|page=5|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=110&dat=19721127&id=vtJOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G0oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6846,4761518}}</ref>

As a junior, Brown again started all 11 games at safety for the [[1973 Michigan Wolverines football team]] that compiled an undefeated 10-0-1 record and allowed opponents to score only 68 points (6.2 points per games).<ref>{{cite web|title=1973 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1973fbt.htm}}</ref>  Brown also returned 14 punts for 125 yards (8.9 yards per return), including a 53-yard return for touchdown against Michigan State. He also contributed 55 tackles and two interceptions.<ref name=SY/> At the end of the year, Brown was selected as a consensus first-team defensive back on the [[1973 College Football All-America Team]].<ref name=CAA>{{cite web|title=2014 NCAA Football Records: Consensus All-America Selections|publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA)|year=2014|accessdate=March 30, 2015|page=8|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2014/Awards.pdf}}</ref> 

As a senior in 1974, Brown once again started all 11 games at safety for the [[1974 Michigan Wolverines football team]] that compiled a 10-1 record, finished the season ranked #3 in the final [[AP Poll]], and allowed opponents to score only 75 points (6.8 points per game).<ref>{{cite web|title=1974 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1974fbt.htm}}</ref>  Brown also returned 20 punts for 212 yards (10.6 yards per return), including an 88-yard return for a touchdown against Colorado.  He also contributed 46 tackles, four pass breakups and four interceptions for the 1974 Wolverines.<ref name=SY/>  At the end of the 1974 season, he was also a unanimous first-team selection to the [[1974 College Football All-America Team]].<ref name=CAA/> 

In three years at Michigan, Brown compiled 526 punt return yards (11.7 yards per return), three punt returns for touchdowns, 174 tackles, nine interceptions, 202 interception return yards, and 15 pass breakups.<ref name=SY/>  During those three years, Michigan compiled a 30-2-1 record, tied for the Big Ten championship each year, led the country in scoring defense twice (and finished second the other year), tallied 11 shutouts and gave up more than 10 points only five times.<ref name=HOF/>  Brown was posthumously inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 2007.<ref name=HOF>{{cite web|title=Dave Brown Member Profile|publisher=National Football Foundation|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://www.footballfoundation.org/Programs/CollegeFootballHallofFame/SearchDetail.aspx?id=90139}}</ref>

==NFL career==
===Pittsburgh Steelers===
Brown was selected by the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the first round (26th overall pick) of the [[1975 NFL Draft]].  As a rookie, he appeared in 13 games, none as a starter, for the [[Super Bowl X]] champion [[1975 Pittsburgh Steelers season|1975 Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref name=PFR/>  Brown also returned 22 punts for 217 yards, an average of 9.9 yards per return, for the 1975 Steelers.<ref name=PFR/>

===Seattle Seahawks===
In the spring of 1976, Brown was chosen by the Seahawks in the NFL expansion draft.<ref name=obit/> Brown joined the Seahawks in their [[1976 Seattle Seahawks season|inaugural 1976 season]] and remained with the club for the first 10 years of the franchise's history.  He appeared in 159 games for the Seahawks, all of them as the team's starting right cornerback.<ref name=PFR/>  In November 1984, the Seahawks established an NFL record with four interception returns (including returns by Brown of 95 and 58 yards) for touchdowns in a single game against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Seahawks' interception crush Chiefs|newspaper=Schenctady Gazette|date=November 5, 1984|page=40|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19841105&id=1xAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=V3MFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2514,1233714&hl=en}}</ref> After the 1984 season, Brown was selected to play in the [[Pro Bowl]] and was also selected by the [[Associated Press]] as a second-team All-NFL player.<ref name=PFR/> 

In his 11 years playing for the Seahawks, Brown established, and continues to hold, franchise records for interceptions (50), interception return yards (643), and interceptions returned for touchdowns (5).<ref name=obit/> In 1992, Brown became the third player inducted into the Seattle Seahawks' "Ring of Honor".<ref name=obit/>

===Green Bay Packers===
In August 1987, the Seahawks traded Brown to the [[Green Bay Packers]] in exchange for a future draft choice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dave Brown: One of the Seahawks' historical figures|author=Dan Weaver|newspaper=Spokane Chonicle|date=August 27, 1987|page=|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1345&dat=19870827&id=dINOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ovoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2155,2249182&hl=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Packer turn a corner with 13-year veteran|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=September 9, 1987|page=C1|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19870909&id=8mwaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rioEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6532,267803&hl=en}}</ref>
Brown played three years with the Packers from 1987 to 1989, appearing in 44 games as the team's starter at right cornerback and registering 12 interceptions.<ref name=PFR/> In July 1990, the Packers placed Brown on the physically unable-to-perform list due to [[tendinitis]] in his [[Achilles tendon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tendinitis benches Brown|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=July 26, 1990|page=C5|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19900725&id=HsAcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3n4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=7086,1519855&hl=en}}</ref>

===Career statistics===
In 15 years in the NFL, Brown appeared in 216 games, 203 of them as a starter.<ref name=PFR/>  He registered 62 career interceptions, which ranks ninth in NFL history.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL Career Interceptions Leaders|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/def_int_career.htm}}</ref> He also registered 698 interception return yards and five interceptions returned for touchdowns.<ref name=PFR/>

==Later years==
After retiring as a player, Brown became a football coach.  He was employed as the Seahawks' defensive backs coach from 1992 to 1998.<ref name=obit/> In 2001, he was hired as the defensive backs coach for the [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football]] team in [[Lubbock, Texas]].  Brown held that position until the time of his death in 2006.<ref name=obit/>  During his tenure, Texas Tech defeated [[Clemson University|Clemson]] 55-15 in the 2002 [[Champs Sports Bowl|Tangerine Bowl]], beat [[United States Naval Academy|Navy]] 38-14 in the 2003 [[Houston Bowl]], beat [[University of California|California]] in the 45-31 in the 2004 [[Holiday Bowl]] and lost to [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] 13-10 in the 2006 [[Cotton Bowl Classic]].

Brown was married and had two sons, Aaron and Sterling, with his wife, Rhonda.<ref name=TT/> On January 10, 2006, Brown died in Lubbock after suffering an apparent [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] while playing [[basketball]] with his son, just six days shy of his 53rd birthday.<ref name=TT>{{cite web|title=Red Raider Family Mourns Loss Of Dave Brown|publisher=Texas Tech University|date=January 10, 2006|accessdate=March 30, 2015|url=http://www.texastech.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/011006aab.html}}</ref><ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=Dave Brown, 1953-2006: Hawks mourn 'class individual'; Ring of Honor great dies from heart attack|author=Clare Farnsworth|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=January 10, 2006|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/football/article/Dave-Brown-1953-2006-Hawks-mourn-class-1192389.php}}</ref>

